item.title: Tattu 1400 6S LiPo Butt and Kidney Guard
item.description:
This is a TPU guard for a 6S Tattu 1400mAH LiPo battery, weighs about 12.5 grams, and it may* help protect from sticks or other sharp objects poking a nice hole in one or more of your cells during your frequent crashes!
The dimensions are set up for a Diatone Roma with two straps, but it could work on plenty of other quads, provided you have your straps in a similar spot. Cut to preference, or stop the print early if you really know what you are doing.
If people like this, I may do some slight variations as requested, and feel free to remix however you want, just don't let me see this on some drop shipping website in a month.

*No guarantees, as always!

item.title: ENDER 3V2 power supply cover 92mm fan silent mod
item.description:
I modified Sectorone's PSU cover that holds a 92mm fan. I made the whole model able to fit on a 220x220 bed. I also added a recess in the model so the model WILL NOT touch the transformer inside the PSU. I also added a hole as a second way to run the fan wires, since the one on the model didnt work for me.
The cover is designed to hold a 92mm fan.
I will provide all the links to the fan and models that i used for the whole project below. My psu fan is now quieter that my parts cooler fan.
you will also need a few other models to work with this. I will also link them. Since i made the model smaller, you will need to print a second piece to cover up the exposed wires. you will understand when you remove the cover.
You will also need to print taller feet/risers for the ENER 3v2.
i also printed a 92mm fan guard.
everything except for the fan guard is required for the mod.

just use the black and yellow wire on the Noctua fan. yellow is +12v. you can just clip the pigtail off the OEM fan and the Noctua fan and solder/crimp the wires together and plug it back in. yellow to red. black to black. The fan mounts on the OUTSIDE of the PSU cover.

DO THE MOD AT YOUR OWN RISK. POWER SUPPLYS CAN BE VERY DANGEROUS. that said, it was fairy easy. no tight spaces and easy to work with.

sadly, i forgot to take pictures during the process and when i was all done.

Noctua 92x14mm fan
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B009NQM7V2/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_asin_title_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

WhisperGod's power supply cover to cover up the exposed wires
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5146129

squirrelf's Ender 3v2 feet risers. I used the 38mm, but would probably use the 45mm if i did it again.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5146129

robertd33's 92mm fan guard. this is optional.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4727426

item.title: BMW E46 Sliding Rear Ashtray Cover Door
item.description:
Hello this is an alternative sliding cover for rear console ashtray in an e46.
Both my brothers and my e46 were missing the covers and its a bit of a pricey piece to replace for what it is.

I printed in PLA+ with layer lines running against the slats to prevent breakage.
Id recommend something like PETG but so far so good in our cars!
Included is a 10min test piece file to check fitment and flexibility of your material.

You can bend bottom of the cover gently to the curve of the slot before inserting first time to make it go in smooth. If the top of the cover with handle isnt flush when first installed you can bend it up a bit until its flat. I did what I had to do make it work with PLA+ so flexible parts between the slats are only 2 layers(.4mm) but no issues still very strong and functional.

I'd love to see some remixes with different handle designs!

enjoy : )

item.title: M3 Knurled Nut - REFERENCE ONLY
item.description:
DISCLAIMER: This model for REFERENCE ONLY.
This is a reference model for an M3 Knurled Nut w/ diameter recommendations.

I have been looking to take my hobby projects and other prints to the next level. I started to implement these knurled nuts via solder heat press into my models for my M3 screws to thread into in order to have much more secure fastening.

This model is based on these knurled nuts that I bought from Amazon:

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07D683Q26/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_asin_title_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

I modeled these nuts as close as I can with my set of calipers based on the nut I received from Amazon.

I have included and engineering drawing of a sample assembly with an M3 screw, M3 knurled nut, and counterbored plastic with my recommended bore diameters.

I put a small 5mm diameter step in the top of the bore so that the knurled nut can be placed directly over & centered over the bore and stay there while the soldering iron tip is heating the nut to melt into the plastic.

Of course, you can play with your diameters to find what suits your project best. These measurements are just what I use.

The last picture of the full assembly is what it would look like fully pressed with a screw threaded in.

item.title: Z height test (.25mm)
item.description:
This is a calibration print to help find the correct z height for your printer!

I designed this specifically for any printer with a .25mm nozzle (but you can use it on others if you want!)

please make sure that you have both your layer hight and initial layer height set to .25mm!

if you measure each step with calipers you can plug your numbers into the excel document I've attached to calculate your new Z offset!

NOTE:
I am not responsible for any damages to your printer if you over or under-adjust your z offset! please print at your own risk!

V3 works great. It is a little wider, and the cut out is oval instead of square.

item.title: Helicopter Automaton
item.description:
Summary Section: The project replicates the movement of a helicopter as it flies in the air using 3D Automation. The Helicopter rotor spins as the person turns the handle as well as moves up and down. The overall dimensions of the project are 20 cm x 8 cm x 16 cm.

This automaton was a lot of fun to design and assemble. After building the first revision of the assembly, I realized that there were many different ways that to change the assembly such as customizing the look of the helicopter as well as changing up the colors so that it looked more appealing. Through creating this project, I significantly improved my Solidworks skills as well as approach to design. If you want a cool automaton that uses rotational cams to show off to your friends and family, I am sure that our helicopter will not disappoint :).

Building this helicopter automaton was a team project. I worked with Nivia Wilson to plan, sketch, create, and assemble this automaton.
